\begin_layout Standard

\lang spanish
Presentamos la transformada de Fourier:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang spanish
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{m}=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}F\left(t\right)e^{-im\omega t}dt
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang spanish
Ahora:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang spanish
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}e^{-i\left(n-m\right)\omega t}dt=\delta_{n,m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang spanish
Ahora, recordando la definición de 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 y obteniendo su transformada de Fourier:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang spanish
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{m}=\frac{1}{T}\int_{0}^{T}\left(\sum_{n}F_{n}e^{in\omega t}\right)e^{-im\omega t}dt=\sum_{n}F_{n}\frac{1}{T}\int e^{i\omega\left(n-m\right)t}=\sum_{n}F_{n}\delta_{n,m}=F_{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang spanish
Ahora, si tenemos una fuerza cualquiera (no tiene por qué ser periódica):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang spanish
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(t\right)=\int F_{\omega}e^{i\omega t}dt
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

